(999, 288, 'sidebar_content', '<strong>The three stages of species revival are distinct ethical domains:</strong>\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>Genomic revival</li>\r\n	<li>Captive breeding</li>\r\n	<li>Return to the wild</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<h4><strong>Relevant links</strong></h4>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><strong> <a href="http://www.bioethics.gov/documents/synthetic-biology/PCSBI-Synthetic-Biology-Report-12.16.10.pdf">The Ethics of Synthetic Biology and Emerging Technologies (From US Presidential Commission, December, 2010)</a></strong></li>\r\n</ul>'),
(1000, 11, 'use_2_column', ''),
(1001, 11, '_use_2_column', 'field_16'),
(1002, 11, 'column_2', ''),
(1003, 11, '_column_2', 'field_17'),
(1004, 11, 'section_1', '<ul>\r\n	<li>If we can revive an extinct species, should we?</li>\r\n	<li>Does it matter if the extinction was caused by humans?</li>\r\n	<li>Will de-extinction research help protect endangered species?</li>\r\n	<li>Are some species more desirable or ethical to bring back than others?</li>\r\n	<li>If the revival process involves interim stages of “chimaeric” (hybrid) creatures, is that a problem?</li>\r\n	<li>If a revived species is not quite genomically identical to the original, how close is close enough?</li>\r\n	<li>Is it ethical to “improve” a revived species—for example to make a formerly extinct bird resistant to avian malaria? (In Hawaii the disease has eliminated most endemic species of birds below 4,000 ft.)</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>What are the consequences of being able to revive a species and deciding not to? Can revival techniques be patented?</li>\r\n	<li>Can revival techniques be kept secret?</li>\r\n	<li>Is it okay to revive a species strictly for commercial purposes?</li>\r\n	<li>As ethical standards emerge, what governance entities are responsible for oversight and enforcement?</li>\r\n	<li>De-extinction could become an amateur medium, the way breeding has. Is there a form of grassroots ethics that could make the practice self-governing?</li>\r\n</ul>'),
(1005, 11, '_section_1', 'field_19'),
(1006, 11, 'section_2', '<ul>\r\n	<li>Is captive breeding of revived species any different from current captive breeding of endangered species?</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>How about creatures or plants that are part way to full revival, such as hybrid band-tailed/passenger pigeons?</li>\r\n</ul>'),
(1007, 11, '_section_2', 'field_23'),
(1008, 11, 'section_3', '<ul>\r\n	<li>Do revived species have a “right” to be returned to the wild?</li>\r\n	<li>Should revived species be treated as invasive species if they are being returned to their former native habitat?</li>\r\n	<li>Should revived species be treated as genetically modified organisms?</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Should Environmental Impact Reports be required before release?</li>\r\n	<li>What kind of ecological analysis should be required before release?</li>\r\n	<li>Is release to the wild irreversible?</li>\r\n</ul>'),
(1009, 11, '_section_3', 'field_24'),
