(1355, 370, '2nd-section-home', '<img class="alignright" style="width: 270px;" alt="" src="http://rare.longnow.org/Resources/p1210136.jpeg" />\r\n<h2>Commencing work on bringing back the passenger pigeon</h2>\r\nWe arranged for grad student <a href="http://rare.longnow.org/projects.html">Ben Novak</a> to intern at George Church’s bioengineering lab at Harvard to refine his sequence data of ancient DNA from three <a href="http://rare.longnow.org/projects.html">passenger pigeon</a> specimens; to begin work on sequencing the band-tailed pigeon (the closest living relative of the passenger pigeon); and to sequence DNA from the mourning dove—a possible hybridizing species with the passenger pigeon. The work will provide necessary foundations for reviving the passenger pigeon and for ecological research important to restoring the species to its native habitat. In the spring of 2013 he joins Beth Shapiro’s ancient-DNA group at UC Santa Cruz.We arranged for grad student Ben Novak to intern at George Church’s bioengineering lab at Harvard to refine his sequence data of ancient DNA from three passenger pigeon specimens; to begin work on sequencing the band-tailed pigeon (the closest living relative of the passenger pigeon); and to sequence DNA from the mourning dove—a possible hybridizing species with the passenger pigeon. The work will provide necessary foundations for reviving the passenger pigeon and for ecological research important to restoring the species to its native habitat. In the spring of 2013 he joins Beth Shapiro’s ancient-DNA group at UC Santa Cruz.'),
(1356, 370, '3rd-section-home', '<img class="alignright" alt="" src="http://media.longnow.org/files/2/rare-isac.jpeg" width="420" height="190" />\r\n<h2>Helping develop norms and <a href="/ethics/">ethics</a> for de-extinction practices.</h2>\r\nStewart Brand and Ryan Phelan were interviewed by Walter Isaacson (author of Steve Jobs; CEO of Aspen Institute) about “Revive and Restore” at the Aspen Environment Forum in June. Video <a href="http://www.aspeninstitute.org/video/2012-aspen-environment-forum-bringing-back-dead-stewart-brand-ryan-phelan">here</a>.'),
(1357, 370, '4th-section-home', '<img class="alignright" alt="" src="http://media.longnow.org/files/2/rare-roster.jpeg" width="247" height="247" />\r\n<h2>Developing a roster of potentiallly revivable species along with criteria that make them more or less practical and desirable to bring back to life.</h2>'),
(1358, 370, '1st-section-home', '<img class="alignright" alt="" src="http://rare.longnow.org/Resources/tedxlive.jpeg" width="281" height="208" />\r\n<h2 class="larger">Convening meetings and workshops of de-extinction pioneers</h2>\r\n<ul class="bottom">\r\n	<li>Convened an exploratory meeting at Harvard in February 2012 on reviving the passenger pigeon. (See report.)</li>\r\n	<li>Organized a private workshop for de-extinction pioneers October 23-24 at National Geographic. (See report.)</li>\r\n	<li>Planning a public conference for de-extinction pioneers and related specialists at National Geographic—TEDx DeExtinction, March 15, 2013. (See meetings.)</li>\r\n</ul>'),
(1359, 370, '5th-section-home', '<h2>Encouraging an online “zoo” of the genomes of revivable extinct species along with the genomes of their closest living relatives. (An excellent genome zoo of living species is the Genome 10K project.)</h2>\r\n<img class="bottom-10" alt="" src="http://media.longnow.org/files/2/rare-genome10k.jpeg" />\r\n<p class="bottom">Ben Novak elaborates:</p>\r\n\r\n<blockquote class="top-10" style="font-size: 1.5em;">“We could create a database exactly like the National Center for Biotechnology Information''s GenBank, only specifically for extinct species, bringing together all the DNA work in one place on this subject. It would be a valuable tool for everyone working in ancient DNA. It could build off the list of "species to bring back". I''m thinking of a full list of extinct species within the age range that DNA is viable to retrieve, with some information on collections housing tissue or fossil material, taxonomy information, and some references to literature. In this way a person designing an ancient DNA project could find out what species have no previous DNA sequenced, what species do, and to what extent. With this list we can then append how suitable a species is for revival.”</blockquote>'),
