(241, 3, '2013-01-22 20:52:53', '2013-01-22 20:52:53', '\r\n<h2>Encouraging an online “zoo” of the genomes of revivable extinct species along with the genomes of their closest living relatives. (An excellent genome zoo of living species is the Genome 10K project.)</h2>\r\n<img class="bottom-10" alt="" src="http://media.longnow.org/files/2/rare-genome10k.jpeg" />\r\n<p class="bottom">Ben Novak elaborates:</p>\r\n\r\n<blockquote class="top-10" style="font-size: 1.5em;">“We could create a database exactly like the National Center for Biotechnology Information''s GenBank, only specifically for extinct species, bringing together all the DNA work in one place on this subject. It would be a valuable tool for everyone working in ancient DNA. It could build off the list of "species to bring back". I''m thinking of a full list of extinct species within the age range that DNA is viable to retrieve, with some information on collections housing tissue or fossil material, taxonomy information, and some references to literature. In this way a person designing an ancient DNA project could find out what species have no previous DNA sequenced, what species do, and to what extent. With this list we can then append how suitable a species is for revival.”</blockquote>', 'Home Page', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '7-revision-41', '', '', '2013-01-22 20:52:53', '2013-01-22 20:52:53', '', 7, 'http://rare.sansink.com/7-revision-41/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
