(313, 3, '2013-01-28 23:32:08', '2013-01-28 23:32:08', '&nbsp;\r\n\r\nThe first two meetings organized by Revive and Restore were private, get-acquainted workshops to determine if reviving extinct species is becoming practical, and if there are molecular biologists and conservation biologists interested in working on it. The Harvard <a href="/ppworshop/">meeting in February 2012 was focussed on the passenger pigeon</a>. <a href="/1stde-extinction/">The National Geographic meeting in October 2012</a> drew 36 scientists from around the world to survey the full range of de-extinction and ecosystem-revival efforts that are being attempted. It was the first such meeting anywhere.\r\n\r\nBoth meetings generated excitement among the participants. Both gave confidence that the subject and its practitioners are ready to go cautiously public. Hence the TEDx public conference scheduled for March 15, 2013.\r\n<div class="span-6">\r\n<p class="larger"><a href="/ppworshop/">Bringing Back the Passenger Pigeon</a></p>\r\nFebruary 8, 2012\r\n\r\nHarvard University, Wyss Institute\r\n\r\n<img alt="" src="http://rare.longnow.org/Resources/freewayproasscre.jpeg" />\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n<div class="span-6">\r\n<p class="larger"><a href="/1stde-extinction/">De-extinction Projects, Techniques, and Ethics</a></p>\r\nOctober 22-23, 2012\r\n\r\nNational Geographic\r\n\r\n<img alt="" src="http://rare.longnow.org/Resources/deextinctiongroua.jpeg" />\r\n\r\n</div>', 'Meetings', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '44-revision-17', '', '', '2013-01-28 23:32:08', '2013-01-28 23:32:08', '', 44, 'http://rare.sansink.com/44-revision-17/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(163, 1, '2013-01-17 21:10:30', '2013-01-17 21:10:30', '<p>The first PUBLIC meeting on de-extinction will take place March 15, 2013, in Washington DC at National Geographic’s Grosvenor Auditorium. It will be a TEDx extravaganza. Ticket information available soon.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The first two meetings organized by Revive and Restore were private, get-acquainted workshops to determine if reviving extinct species is becoming practical, and if there are molecular biologists and conservation biologists interested in working on it. The Harvard meeting in February 2012 was focussed on the passenger pigeon. The National Geographic meeting in October 2012 drew 36 scientists from around the world to survey the full range of de-extinction and ecosystem-revival efforts that are being attempted. It was the first such meeting anywhere.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Both meetings generated excitement among the participants. Both gave confidence that the subject and its practitioners are ready to go cautiously public. Hence the TEDx public conference scheduled for March 15, 2013.</p>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<div class="span-6">\r\n\r\n    <p class="larger"><a href="">Bringing Back the Passenger Pigeon</a></p>\r\n\r\n    <p>February 8, 2012<br />\r\n    \r\n        Harvard University, Wyss Institute</p>\r\n\r\n        <img src="http://rare.longnow.org/Resources/freewayproasscre.jpeg">\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n    \r\n        \r\n        \r\n    \r\n\r\n<div class="span-6">\r\n\r\n    <p class="larger"><a href="">De-extinction Projects, Techniques, and Ethics</a></p>\r\n\r\n    <p>October 22-23, 2012<br />\r\n\r\n        National Geographic</p>\r\n\r\n    <img src="http://rare.longnow.org/Resources/deextinctiongroua.jpeg" alt="">\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n        \r\n        \r\n        \r\n    \r\n        \r\n<div class="span-6">\r\n\r\n    <p class="larger"><a href="">TEDxDeExtinction</a></p>\r\n\r\n    <p>March 15, 2013<br />\r\n\r\n        National Geographic</p>\r\n\r\n    <img src="http://rare.longnow.org/Resources/tedxlive.jpeg" alt="">\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n', 'Meetings', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '44-revision-6', '', '', '2013-01-17 21:10:30', '2013-01-17 21:10:30', '', 44, 'http://rare.sansink.com/44-revision-6/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(162, 1, '2013-01-17 21:10:06', '2013-01-17 21:10:06', '<style type="text/css">\r\n    .body_block {\r\n    font-size: 1.12em;\r\n    }\r\n    .body_block ul li {\r\n    margin-bottom: 4px;\r\n    }\r\n    .body_block h1 {\r\n    color: #94907e;\r\n    }\r\n    .body_block h2 {\r\n    font-size: 2em;\r\n    line-height: 1.2em;\r\n    font-family: "Helvetica Neue", Helvetica, Verdana, Arial, sans-serif;\r\n    }\r\n    .body_block ul {\r\n    margin-left: 30px;\r\n    }\r\n    .header_block form {\r\n    display: none;\r\n    }\r\n    .menu_block {\r\n    display: none;\r\n    }\r\n    .user_menu_block div {\r\n    display: none;\r\n    }\r\n</style>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<p>The first PUBLIC meeting on de-extinction will take place March 15, 2013, in Washington DC at National Geographic’s Grosvenor Auditorium. It will be a TEDx extravaganza. Ticket information available soon.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The first two meetings organized by Revive and Restore were private, get-acquainted workshops to determine if reviving extinct species is becoming practical, and if there are molecular biologists and conservation biologists interested in working on it. The Harvard meeting in February 2012 was focussed on the passenger pigeon. The National Geographic meeting in October 2012 drew 36 scientists from around the world to survey the full range of de-extinction and ecosystem-revival efforts that are being attempted. It was the first such meeting anywhere.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Both meetings generated excitement among the participants. Both gave confidence that the subject and its practitioners are ready to go cautiously public. Hence the TEDx public conference scheduled for March 15, 2013.</p>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<div class="span-6">\r\n\r\n    <p class="larger"><a href="">Bringing Back the Passenger Pigeon</a></p>\r\n\r\n    <p>February 8, 2012<br />\r\n    \r\n        Harvard University, Wyss Institute</p>\r\n\r\n        <img src="http://rare.longnow.org/Resources/freewayproasscre.jpeg">\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n 