(47, 1, '2013-01-17 17:43:40', '2013-01-17 17:43:40', '	<table border="0" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" width="933">\r\n		<colgroup>\r\n			<col width="61">\r\n			<col width="871">\r\n			<col width="1">\r\n		</colgroup>\r\n		<tbody><tr valign="top">\r\n			<td height="296"></td>\r\n			<td style="border:solid #000 1px; padding:25px" bgcolor="#ffffff" height="244"><p><span class="style14">The first PUBLIC meeting on de-extinction will take place March 15, 2013, in Washington DC at National Geographic’s Grosvenor Auditorium.  It will be a TEDx extravaganza.  Ticket information available soon.</span></p>\r\n			<p><span class="style7"><span class="style40">The first two meetings organized by Revive and Restore were private, get-acquainted workshops to determine if reviving extinct species is becoming practical, and if there are molecular biologists and conservation biologists interested in working on it.  The Harvard </span><a href="ppworshop.html"><span class="style40">meeting in February 2012 was focussed on the passenger pigeon.</span></a><span class="style40">  The </span><a href="1stde-extinction.html"><span class="style40">National Geographic meeting in October 2012</span></a><span class="style40"> drew 36 scientists from around the world to survey the full range of de-extinction and ecosystem-revival efforts that are being attempted.  It was the first such meeting anywhere.</span></span></p>\r\n			<p class="f-lp"><span class="style14">Both meetings generated excitement among the participants.  Both gave confidence that the subject and its practitioners are ready to go cautiously public.  Hence the TEDx public conference scheduled for March 15, 2013.</span></p>\r\n			</td>\r\n			<td height="296"></td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr class="f-sp">\r\n			<td><img src="Resources/_clear.gif" alt="" style="float:left" border="0" height="1" width="61"></td>\r\n			<td><img src="Resources/_clear.gif" alt="" style="float:left" border="0" height="1" width="871"></td>\r\n			<td height="1