(217, 3, '2013-01-22 19:56:17', '2013-01-22 19:56:17', '<style type="text/css"><!--\r\n\r\n.roster_wrapper {\r\n    padding-top: 30px;\r\n    position: relative;\r\n    left: -80px;\r\n    margin: 25px 0 25px;\r\n    padding-left: 80px;\r\n    background: url(http://media.longnow.org/files/2/rare-roster-bg.jpeg) center center no-repeat;\r\n    width: 870px;\r\n    height: 280px;\r\n    display: block;\r\n    }\r\n    .roster_wrapper h2 {\r\n    color: #42413b;\r\n    }\r\n    .tedx_wrapper {\r\n    padding-top: 25px;\r\n    position: relative;\r\n    left: -40px;\r\n    margin: 20px 0 20px 0;\r\n    padding-left: 40px;\r\n    background: white;\r\n    width: 830px;\r\n    height: 260px;\r\n    display: block;\r\n    }\r\n--></style>\r\n<h1>Current Activities</h1>\r\n\r\n<div class="span-12 append-1">\r\n<h2>Commencing work on bringing back the passenger pigeon</h2>\r\nWe arranged for grad student <a href="http://rare.longnow.org/projects.html">Ben Novak</a> to intern at George Church’s bioengineering lab at Harvard to refine his sequence data of ancient DNA from three <a href="http://rare.longnow.org/projects.html">passenger pigeon</a> specimens; to begin work on sequencing the band-tailed pigeon (the closest living relative of the passenger pigeon); and to sequence DNA from the mourning dove—a possible hybridizing species with the passenger pigeon. The work will provide necessary foundations for reviving the passenger pigeon and for ecological research important to restoring the species to its native habitat. In the spring of 2013 he joins Beth Shapiro’s ancient-DNA group at UC Santa Cruz.We arranged for grad student Ben Novak to intern at George Church’s bioengineering lab at Harvard to refine his sequence data of ancient DNA from three passenger pigeon specimens; to begin work on sequencing the band-tailed pigeon (the closest living relative of the passenger pigeon); and to sequence DNA from the mourning dove—a possible hybridizing species with the passenger pigeon. The work will provide necessary foundations for reviving the passenger pigeon and for ecological research important to restoring the species to its native habitat. In the spring of 2013 he joins Beth Shapiro’s ancient-DNA group at UC Santa Cruz.\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n<div class="span-7 last"><img style="width: 270px;" alt="" src="http://rare.longnow.org/Resources/p1210136.jpeg" /></div>\r\n<div class="dotted_break bottom-30 spacer-10"></div>\r\n<img class="float_right" style="width: 509px; margin-left: 15px;" alt="" src="http://media.longnow.org/files/2/rare-isac.jpeg" />\r\n<h2>Helping develop norms and <a href="/ethics/">ethics</a> for de-extinction practices.</h2>\r\nStewart Brand and Ryan Phelan were interviewed by Walter Isaacson (author of Steve Jobs; CEO of Aspen Institute) about “Revive and Restore” at the Aspen Environment Forum in June. Video <a href="http://www.aspeninstitute.org/video/2012-aspen-environment-forum-bringing-back-dead-stewart-brand-ryan-phelan">here</a>.\r\n<div class="roster_wrapper">\r\n<div class="span-13">\r\n<div class="spacer-60"></div>\r\n<h2>Developing a roster of potentiallly revivable species along with criteria that make them more or less practical and desirable to bring back to life.</h2>\r\n</div>\r\n<div class="span-7 last right"><img alt="" src="http://media.longnow.org/files/2/rare-roster.jpeg" /></div>\r\n</div>\r\n<h2>Encouraging an online “zoo” of the genomes of revivable extinct species along with the genomes of their closest living relatives. (An excellent genome zoo of living species is the Genome 10K project.)</h2>\r\n<img class="bottom-10" alt="" src="http://media.longnow.org/files/2/rare-genome10k.jpeg" />\r\n<p class="bottom">Ben Novak elaborates:</p>\r\n\r\n<blockquote class="top-10" style="font-size: 1.5em;">“We could create a database exactly like the National Center for Biotechnology Information''s GenBank, only specifically for extinct species, bringing together all the DNA work in one place on this subject. It would be a valuable tool for everyone working in ancient DNA. It could build off the list of "species to bring back". I''m thinking of a full list of extinct species within the age range that DNA is viable to retrieve, with some information on collections housing tissue or fossil material, taxonomy information, and some references to literature. In this way a person designing an ancient DNA project could find out what species have no previous DNA sequenced, what species do, and to what extent. With this list we can then append how suitable a species is for revival.”</blockquote>', 'Home Page', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '7-revision-17', '', '', '2013-01-22 19:56:17', '2013-01-22 19:56:17', '', 7, 'http://rare.sansink.com/7-revision-17/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(210, 3, '2013-01-17 21:35:24', '2013-01-17 21:35:24', '<h1>Ethics</h1>\r\n<strong>The three stages of species revival are distinct ethical domains:</strong>\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>Genomic revival</li>\r\n	<li>Captive breeding</li>\r\n	<li>Return to the wild</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<strong>Relevant link: <a href="http://www.bioethics.gov/documents/synthetic-biology/PCSBI-Synthetic-Biology-Report-12.16.10.pdf">The Ethics of Synthetic Biology and Emerging Technologies (From US Presidential Commission, December, 2010)</a></strong>\r\n<h2><strong>Genomic revival questions</strong></h2>\r\nIf we can revive an extinct species, should we?\r\n\r\nDoes it matter if the extinction was caused by humans?\r\n\r\nWill de-extinction research help protect endangered species?\r\n\r\nAre some species more desirable or ethical to bring back than others?\r\n\r\nIf the revival process involves interim stages of “chimaeric” (hybrid) creatures, is that a problem?\r\n\r\nIf a revived species is not quite genomically identical to the original, how close is close enough?\r\n\r\nIs it ethical to “improve” a revived species—for example to make a formerly extinct bird resistant to avian malaria? (In Hawaii the disease has eliminated most endemic species of birds below 4,000 ft.)\r\n\r\nWhat are the consequences of being able to revive a species and deciding not to? Can revival techniques be patented?\r\n\r\nCan revival techniques be kept secret?\r\n\r\nIs it okay to revive a species strictly for commercial purposes?\r\n\r\nAs ethical standards emerge, what governance entities are responsible for oversight and enforcement?\r\n\r\nDe-extinction could become an amateur medium, the way breeding has. Is there a form of grassroots ethics that could make the practice self-governing?\r\n<h2><strong>Captive breeding questions</strong></h2>\r\nIs captive breeding of revived species any different from current captive breeding of endangered species?\r\n\r\nHow about creatures or plants that are part way to full revival, such as hybrid band-tailed/passenger pigeons?\r\n<h2><strong>Return-to-the-wild questions</strong></h2>\r\nDo revived species have a “right” to be returned to the wild?\r\n\r\nShould revived species be treated as invasive species if they are being returned to their former native habitat?\r\n\r\nShould revived species be treated as genetically modified organisms?\r\n\r\nShould Environmental Impact Reports be required before release?\r\n\r\nWhat kind of ecological analysis should be required before release?\r\n\r\nIs release to the wild irreversible?', 'Ethics', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '11-revision-6', '', '', '2013-01-17 21:35:24', '2013-01-17 21:35:24', '', 11, 'http://rare.sansink.com/11-revision-6/', 0, 'revision', '', 0);
