(258, 3, '2013-01-22 19:45:37', '2013-01-22 19:45:37', '<strong>The three stages of species revival are distinct ethical domains:</strong>\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>Genomic revival</li>\r\n	<li>Captive breeding</li>\r\n	<li>Return to the wild</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<strong>Relevant link: <a href="http://www.bioethics.gov/documents/synthetic-biology/PCSBI-Synthetic-Biology-Report-12.16.10.pdf">The Ethics of Synthetic Biology and Emerging Technologies (From US Presidential Commission, December, 2010)</a></strong>\r\n<h2><strong>Genomic revival questions</strong></h2>\r\nIf we can revive an extinct species, should we?\r\n\r\nDoes it matter if the extinction was caused by humans?\r\n\r\nWill de-extinction research help protect endangered species?\r\n\r\nAre some species more desirable or ethical to bring back than others?\r\n\r\nIf the revival process involves interim stages of “chimaeric” (hybrid) creatures, is that a problem?\r\n\r\nIf a revived species is not quite genomically identical to the original, how close is close enough?\r\n\r\nIs it ethical to “improve” a revived species—for example to make a formerly extinct bird resistant to avian malaria? (In Hawaii the disease has eliminated most endemic species of birds below 4,000 ft.)\r\n\r\nWhat are the consequences of being able to revive a species and deciding not to? Can revival techniques be patented?\r\n\r\nCan revival techniques be kept secret?\r\n\r\nIs it okay to revive a species strictly for commercial purposes?\r\n\r\nAs ethical standards emerge, what governance entities are responsible for oversight and enforcement?\r\n\r\nDe-extinction could become an amateur medium, the way breeding has. Is there a form of grassroots ethics that could make the practice self-governing?\r\n<h2><strong>Captive breeding questions</strong></h2>\r\nIs captive breeding of revived species any different from current captive breeding of endangered species?\r\n\r\nHow about creatures or plants that are part way to full revival, such as hybrid band-tailed/passenger pigeons?\r\n<h2><strong>Return-to-the-wild questions</strong></h2>\r\nDo revived species have a “right” to be returned to the wild?\r\n\r\nShould revived species be treated as invasive species if they are being returned to their former native habitat?\r\n\r\nShould revived species be treated as genetically modified organisms?\r\n\r\nShould Environmental Impact Reports be required before release?\r\n\r\nWhat kind of ecological analysis should be required before release?\r\n\r\nIs release to the wild irreversible?', 'Ethics', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '11-revision-7', '', '', '2013-01-22 19:45:37', '2013-01-22 19:45:37', '', 11, 'http://rare.sansink.com/11-revision-7/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
